In article <58035@cup.portal.com> Christopher_C_Lapp@cup.portal.com writes:
>The concept of plaintext encryption (defined as encryption
>that has as its output factual, rational, coherent, and informative
>text) has basically destroyed the ability of the NSA to find
>encrypted text, let alone decrypt it.  When everything looks
>and feels like simple plaintext, there is nothing to focus the
>eavesdropping supercomputer on.  

I think we have to assume NSA knows what messages it wants to listen 
to, eg, messages from known spies. Actually, the problem is the opposite
of the one you state: with the spreading use of better and better 
data compression, all messages look like ciphertext, not plaintext.
